or, and the formation of an information-intensive New Economy. By examining his own evolving interpretations of Los Angeles and the debates on the so-called Los Angeles School of urban studies, Soja argues that a radical shift is taking place in the nature of the urbanization process, from the familiar metropolitan model to regional urbanization. By looking at such concepts as new regionalism, the spatial turn, the end of the metropolis era, the urbanization of suburbia, the global spread of industrial urbanism, and the transformative urban-industrialization of China, Soja offers a unique and remarkable perspective on critical urban and regional studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aRegional planningzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aSociology, UrbanzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  aamerican metropolis.  acalifornia.  acalifornian history.  acapital and labor.  acity life.  acity regions.  acrowded cities.  adeindustrialization.  aglobalization.  aheterogeneous.  ahistory of los angeles.  ahistory.  alos angeles school of urban studies.  alos angeles.  ametropolis era.  anew economy.  anew regionalism.  apolitics.  aregional studies.  aregional urbanization.  areindustrialization.  aspatial turn.  aunited states of america.  aurban development.  aurban restructuring.  aurban studies.  aurban.  aurbanization of suburbia.  aurbanization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028174540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095763340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780